SIMPLE: husk
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Husk
<hw>Husk</hw> <pr>(h⟦ucr⟧sk)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. for
<ets>hulsk</ets>, and from the same root as <ets>hull</ets> a husk. See
<er>Hull</er> a husk.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The external covering or
envelope of certain fruits or seeds; glume; hull; rind; in the United
States, especially applied to the covering of the ears of
maize.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The supporting frame of a run of
millstones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Husks of the prodigal son</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>,
<cd>the pods of the carob tree. See <er>Carob</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Husk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Husk
<hw>Husk</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Husked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Husking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To strip off the external
covering or envelope of; <as>as, to <ex>husk</ex> Indian
corn</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Husked</ent>⟦br⟧
